tatistics of edge elements in images of{\textbackslash}nnatural scenes, and compared them to corresponding{\textbackslash}nstatistics for images taken from within the rearing{\textbackslash}nenvironment of the animals in the Bosking et{\textbackslash}nal. (1997) study. We used a modified version of the{\textbackslash}nalgorithm from Geisler et al. (2001), with a moreŋeneral edge extraction algorithm that uses sparse{\textbackslash}ncoding to avoid multiple responses to a single{\textbackslash}nedge. Collinearity and co-circularity results for{\textbackslash}nnatural images replicated qualitatively the results{\textbackslash}nfrom Geisler et al. (2001), confirming that prior{\textbackslash}ninformation about continuations appeared{\textbackslash}nconsistently in natural images. However, we find{\textbackslash}nthat the largely man-made environment in which these{\textbackslash}nanimals were reared has a significantly higher{\textbackslash}nprobability of collinear edge elements. We thus{\textbackslash}npredict that if the lateral connection patterns are{\textbackslash}ndue to visual experience, the patterns in{\textbackslash}nwild-raised tree shrews would be very different from{\textbackslash}nthose measured by Bosking et al. (1997), with{\textbackslash}nshorter-range correlations and less emphasis on{\textbackslash}ncollinear continuations. This prediction can be{\textbackslash}ntested in future experiments on matching groups of{\textbackslash}nanimals reared in different environments.},
