	abstract = {The integration of information is essential to measure the exact 2D{\textbackslash}nmotion of a surface from both local ambiguous 1D motion produced{\textbackslash}nby elongated edges and local non-ambiguous 2D motion from features{\textbackslash}nsuch as corners, end-points or texture elements. The dynamics of{\textbackslash}nthis motion integration shows a complex time course which can be{\textbackslash}nread from tracking eye movements: local 1D motion signals are extracted{\textbackslash}nfirst and then pooled to initiate the ocular responses before that{\textbackslash}n2D motion signals are taken into account to refine the tracking direction{\textbackslash}nuntil it matches the surface motion direction. The nature of these{\textbackslash}n1D and 2D motion computations is still unclear. Previously, we have{\textbackslash}nshown that the late, 2D-driven response components to either plaids{\textbackslash}nor barber-poles have very similar latencies over a large range of{\textbackslash}ncontrast, suggesting a shared mechanism. However, they showed different{\textbackslash}ncontrast response functions with these different motion stimuli,{\textbackslash}nsuggesting different motion processing. We designed a two-pathways{\textbackslash}{nBayesian} model of motion integration and showed that this family{\textbackslash}nof contrast response functions can be predicted from the probability{\textbackslash}ndistributions of 1D and 2D motion signals for each type of stimulus.{\textbackslash}{nIndeed}, this formulation may explain contrast response functions{\textbackslash}nthat could not be explained by a simple bayesian model (Weiss et{\textbackslash}nal., 2002 {\textbackslash}em Nature Neuroscience {\textbackslash}bf 5 , 598–604) and gives{\textbackslash}na quantitative argument to study how local information with different{\textbackslash}nrelative ambiguities values may be pooled to provide an integrated{\textbackslash}nresponse of the system. Finally, we formulate how different spatial{\textbackslash}ninformation may be pooled and we draw the analogy of this method{\textbackslash}nwith methods using the partial derivative equations. This simple{\textbackslash}nmodel correctly explains some non-linear interactions between neighboring{\textbackslash}nneurons selective to motion direction which are observed in short-latency{\textbackslash}nocular following and neuro-physiological data.},
