	doi = {10/bjz68g},
	abstract = {The smooth pursuit eye movement system uses retinal{\textbackslash}ninformation about the image-slip-velocity of the target{\textbackslash}nin order to match the eye-velocity-in-space (i.e.,{\textbackslash}ngaze-velocity) to the actual target velocity. To{\textbackslash}nmaintain the target image on the fovea during smooth{\textbackslash}ngaze tracking, and to compensate for the long delays{\textbackslash}ninvolved in processing visual motion information and/or{\textbackslash}neye velocity commands, the pursuit system must use{\textbackslash}nprediction. We have shown recently that both retinal{\textbackslash}nimage-slip-velocity and gaze-velocity signals are coded{\textbackslash}nin the discharge of single pursuit-related neurons in{\textbackslash}nthe simian periarcuate cortex. To understand how{\textbackslash}nperiarcuate pursuit neurons are involved in predictive{\textbackslash}nsmooth pursuit, we examined the discharge{\textbackslash}ncharacteristics of these neurons in trained Japanese{\textbackslash}nmacaques. When a stationary target abruptly moved{\textbackslash}nsinusoidally along the preferred direction at 0.5 Hz,{\textbackslash}nthe response delays of pursuit cells seen at the onset{\textbackslash}nof target motion were compensated in succeeding cycles.{\textbackslash}{nThe} monkeys were also required to continue smooth{\textbackslash}npursuit of a sinusoidally moving target while it was{\textbackslash}nblanked for about half of a cycle at 0.5 Hz. This{\textbackslash}nblanking was applied before cell activity normally{\textbackslash}nincreased and before the target changed direction.{\textbackslash}{nNormalized} mean gain of the cells' responses (re{\textbackslash}ncontrol value without blanking) decreased to{\textbackslash}n0.81(+/-0.67 {SD}), whereas normalized mean gain of the{\textbackslash}neye movement (eye gain) decreased to 0.65 (+/-0.16 {SD}).{\textbackslash}{nA} majority (75\%) of pursuit neurons discharged{\textbackslash}nappropri