	abstract = {Numerical and computer-graphic methods for conformal image mapping{\textbackslash}nbetween two simply connected regions are described. The immediate{\textbackslash}nmotivation for this application is that the visual field is represented{\textbackslash}nin the brain by mappings which are, at least approximately, conformal.{\textbackslash}{nThus}, to simulate the imaging properties of the human visual system (and{\textbackslash}nperhaps other sensory systems), conformal image mapping is a necessary{\textbackslash}ntechnique. For generating the conformal map, a method for analytic{\textbackslash}nmappings and an implementation of the Symm algorithm for numerical{\textbackslash}nconformal mapping are shown. The first method evaluates the inverse{\textbackslash}nmapping function at each pixel of the range, with antialiasing by{\textbackslash}nmultiresolution texture prefiltering and bilinear interpolation. The{\textbackslash}nsecond method is based on constructing a piecewise affine approximation{\textbackslash}nof the mapping in the form of a joint triangulation, or triangulation{\textbackslash}nmap, in which only the nodes of the triangulation are conformally{\textbackslash}nmapped. The texture is then mapped by a local affine transformation on{\textbackslash}neach pixel of the range triangulation with the same antialiasing used in{\textbackslash}nthe first method. The algorithms are illustrated with examples of{\textbackslash}nconformal mappings constructed analytically from elementary mappings,{\textbackslash}nsuch as the linear fractional map, the complex algorithm, etc.{\textbackslash}{nApplications} of numerically generated maps between highly irregular{\textbackslash}nregions and an example of the visual field mapping that motivates this{\textbackslash}nwork are also shown},
