	abstract = {In the primary visual cortex (V1), single cell responses to simple{\textbackslash}nvisual stimuli (gratings) are usually dense but with a high trial-by-trial{\textbackslash}nvariability. In contrast, when exposed to full field natural scenes,{\textbackslash}nthe firing patterns of these neurons are sparse but highly reproducible{\textbackslash}nover trials (Marre et al., 2005; Frégnac et al., 2006). It is{\textbackslash}nstill not understood how these two classes of stimuli can elicit{\textbackslash}nthese two distinct firing behaviours. A common model for simple-cell{\textbackslash}ncomputation in layer 4 is the “push-pull” circuitry (Troyer et{\textbackslash}nal. 1998). It accounts for the observed anti-phase behaviour between{\textbackslash}nexcitatory and inhibitory conductances in response to a driftingŋrating (Anderson et al., 2000; Monier et al., 2008), creating a{\textbackslash}nwide temporal integration window during which excitation is integrated{\textbackslash}nwithout the shunting or opponent effect of inhibition and allowed{\textbackslash}nto elicit multiple spikes. This is in contrast to recent results{\textbackslash}nfrom intracellular recordings in vivo during presentation of natural{\textbackslash}nscenes (Baudot et al., submitted). Here the excitatory and inhibitory{\textbackslash}nconductances were highly correlated, with inhibition lagging excitation{\textbackslash}nonly by few milliseconds (\${\textbackslash}sim\$6 ms). This small lag creates a narrow{\textbackslash}ntemporal integration window such that only synchronized excitatory{\textbackslash}ninputs can elicit a spike, similar to parallel observations in other{\textbackslash}ncortical sensory areas (Wehr and Zador, 2003; Okun and Lampl, 2008).{\textbackslash}{nTo} investigate the cellular and network mechanisms underlying these{\textbackslash}ntwo different correlation structures, we constructed a realistic{\textbackslash}nmodel of the V1 network using spiking neurons with conductance based{\textbackslash}nsynapses. We calibrated our model to fit the irregular ongoing activity{\textbackslash}npattern as well as in vivo conductance measurements during driftingŋrating stimulation and then extracted predicted responses to natural{\textbackslash}nscenes seen through eye-movements. Our simulations reproduced the{\textbackslash}nabove described experimental observation, together with anti-phase{\textbackslash}nbehaviour between excitation and inhibition during gratings and phase{\textbackslash}nlagged activation during natural scenes. In conclusion, the same{\textbackslash}ncortical network that shows dense and variable responses to gratings{\textbackslash}nexhibits sparse and precise spiking to natural scenes. Work is under{\textbackslash}nway to show to which extent this feature is specific for the feedforward{\textbackslash}nvs recurrent nature of the modelled circuit.},
